Penny Taylor scored 16 points and LaToya
Thomas added 14 as the Cleveland Rockers withstood a second-half
run by the Washington Mystics to win 72-68 Saturday night.
article.headline: Holdsclaw has 22 points in loss
article.linkText: Rockers hold off late Mystics' rally to pull out win
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Penny Taylor scored 16 points and LaToya Thomas added 14 as the Cleveland Rockers withstood a second-half run by the Washington Mystics to win 72-68 Saturday night.

Cleveland led by as many as 14 points in the first half, but Washington (9-22) rallied early in the second and led 62-61 with 5:08 to play.

The Rockers (15-14) moved back in front, this time for good, taking a 72-68 lead with 7.6 seconds left. Washington had a chance to cut into Cleveland's advantage, but Stacey Dales-Schuman missed a 3-point attempt and Kiesha Brown airballed a jumper.

The Rockers' game Thursday night was postponed because of the blackout, and Taylor said Cleveland was ready for its matchup with the Mystics.

"We had extra time to prepare because of our game being canceled," she said. "We knew coming here they have good form, and playing a team with Chamique Holdsclaw, a big focus was defense."

Holdsclaw led all players with 20 points and 13 rebounds, but
the Mystics' second-half charge came up just short.

"Cleveland is a great team, when we made a run they answered,"
Washington center Murriel Page said. "It just so happened that we
ended up on the losing end of the game."

Chasity Melvin scored 13 points for Cleveland.
